## 3. Core operations

There are really only two fundamental operations, and everything else is built on them.

### Insert → sift-up (bubble-up)

Append the new element to the end of the array, then repeatedly swap it with its parent while it's smaller than its parent. The new element "bubbles up" to its correct position.

Time: **O(log n)** — the tree height is `⌊log₂ n⌋`, so at most that many swaps.

### Extract-min → sift-down (bubble-down)

Swap the root with the last element, remove the last element (which was the minimum), then push the new root downward — at each step, swapping with the *smaller* of its two children. This restores the heap property.

Time: **O(log n)** — at most one swap per level.

### Heapify (building from an array) → O(n)

This one surprises people. To build a heap from an arbitrary array, you call sift-down on every non-leaf node, starting from the last non-leaf (`n//2 - 1`) and going up to the root.

Why O(n) and not O(n log n)? Because most nodes are near the bottom where sift-down is cheap. Half the nodes are leaves (0 work), a quarter can sink at most 1 level, an eighth at most 2, and so on. The sum of this geometric series converges to O(n). This is actually a non-trivial result — the proof uses the summation `∑ k/2^k = 2`.

