## 5. Python's `heapq` module

Python's `heapq` implements a **min-heap only**. It operates on plain lists in-place — there is no `Heap` class.

```python
import heapq

# Build from existing list — O(n)
data = [5, 3, 8, 1, 9, 2, 7]
heapq.heapify(data)          # transforms data IN-PLACE
print(data[0])               # 1 — the minimum, always at index 0

# Insert — O(log n)
heapq.heappush(data, 4)

# Extract min — O(log n)
minimum = heapq.heappop(data)

# Peek min without removing — O(1)
minimum = data[0]

# Efficient combined operations
heapq.heappushpop(data, 6)   # push then pop (one sift, not two)
heapq.heapreplace(data, 6)   # pop then push (faster than separate calls)

# Convenience utilities — work on any iterable, not just a heap
heapq.nsmallest(3, data)     # O(n log k)
heapq.nlargest(3, data)      # O(n log k)
```

**Critical Python-specific rules:**

`heapify` is O(n) — this is not `n` calls to `heappush`. Never do `for x in data: heapq.heappush(h, x)` to build from scratch when you have all elements upfront; use `heapify`.

`heappop` returns and removes the root. `data[0]` just peeks. Do not confuse them.

The list after `heapify` is **not sorted** — it's only heap-ordered. `data[1]` is not necessarily the second smallest.

