## 6. The max-heap trick

Python has no built-in max-heap. The standard trick: **negate all values**.

```python
import heapq

# Max-heap by negating
h = []
for val in [3, 1, 8, 5, 2]:
    heapq.heappush(h, -val)   # store negative

maximum = -heapq.heappop(h)   # negate on the way out → 8

# Or to heapify in-place:
data = [3, 1, 8, 5, 2]
data = [-x for x in data]
heapq.heapify(data)
maximum = -heapq.heappop(data)
```

For **tuples** (the more common pattern), the heap sorts by the first element, then second, etc. This lets you attach metadata:

```python
# Priority queue pattern: (priority, item)
h = []
heapq.heappush(h, (2, 'task_b'))
heapq.heappush(h, (1, 'task_a'))   # lower number = higher priority
heapq.heappush(h, (3, 'task_c'))

priority, task = heapq.heappop(h)  # (1, 'task_a')

# Max-heap with tuples: negate the priority
heapq.heappush(h, (-score, item))
_, best = heapq.heappop(h)
```

One gotcha: if two tuples have the same first element, Python will compare the second element. If your items aren't comparable (e.g. custom objects), add a tie-breaking counter as the second element:

```python
counter = 0
heapq.heappush(h, (priority, counter, item))
counter += 1
```

